content.text:
An exhaustive switch is one where the compiler can prove every possible value of the switch subject is handled — so if someone later adds a new member to the type, the build breaks instead of silently falling through.

The usual pattern in TypeScript:

```ts
function assertNever(x: never): never {
  throw new Error(`Unhandled case: ${JSON.stringify(x)}`);
}

switch (table) {
  case 'foo':
    icon = <FooIcon />;
    break;
  case 'bar':
    icon = <BarIcon />;
    break;
  default:
    assertNever(table); // table's type here should be `never` if all cases are handled
}
```

Why this works: after all real cases are handled, TypeScript narrows `table`'s type in the `default` branch to `never` (the empty type — "no value should reach here"). `assertNever` only accepts `never`, so:

- **Today**: if every case is covered, the code compiles fine.
- **Later**: if someone adds a new value to the `table` union/enum but forgets to add a `case` for it, TypeScript narrows the leftover type in `default` to include that new member — which is no longer assignable to `never` — so the call to `assertNever(table)` becomes a **type error**, failing the build at compile time.
- **At runtime**: if this code path is ever reached with a value that wasn't statically anticipated (e.g. bad data), it throws instead of leaving `icon` as `undefined`.

The comment is flagging that the current switch has no `default` at all, so if `table`'s type grows a new variant, `icon` just quietly stays `undefined` — no compiler error, no runtime error, just a missing icon that someone has to notice visually. The fix is either:
1. A `default: assertNever(table)` for full compile-time exhaustiveness, or
2. At minimum a `default: throw new Error(...)` so it fails loudly at runtime even without the compile-time guarantee.

If you want, I can look at the actual file this comment applies to and apply the fix.

